{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ee8e7bb9-e28f-4834-9458-f5aeb262956c","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_015zw4ooGvWKrXpmBZJMksxz","name":"view","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-aa4966df412b4a7b8e9a564cca9d0a89"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"view the file at /tmp/sv-aa4966df412b4a7b8e9a564cca9d0a89."}],"interactionId":"d56912d6-a2e8-409b-883a-b366e23e55ff","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check for required and recommended fields.\n\nIssues I can see:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not strictly required, but highly recommended for validation and editor support. The standard schema URL is `http://json.schemastore.org/template`.\n\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet packages, especially if you plan to have multiple related templates.\n\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Useful when multiple versions of the template exist.\n\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Common for project templates.\n\n\nThe core fields like `sourceName`, `identity`, `shortName`, `author`, `classifications`, and `tags` are all present, which is good. However, there's a critical issue with the `Framework` symbol — it's missing the `replaces` property, which means the framework parameter won't actually substitute values into your template files. You'd typically want something like `\"replaces\": \"net9.0\"` so the selected framework gets injected where needed.\n\nI should also verify whether there are other files in the template package beyond just the `template.json`, since those would be part of what gets generated.","outputTokens":515,"requestId":"0407:1B520F:ACF202:D7753B:6A012AF6"},"id":"7b76f3e9-4106-439f-b447-ac591b618f8c","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:04:02.789Z","parentId":"bc2474ad-a0e4-4f0d-b690-0362638d7848"}
